<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFFC7FFC6D495E127535B1B8F" box="[199,1049,1904,1929]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="91193695FFC7FFC6D495E127535B1B8F" blockId="27.[151,1437,253,2037]" box="[199,1049,1904,1929]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC7FFC6D495E127560C1B8F" bold="true" box="[199,334,1904,1929]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after João Cardoso, the collector of the 
<typeStatus id="4E1D8837FFC7FFC6D734E12654D41B8F" box="[870,918,1905,1929]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">type</typeStatus>
specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFFC7FFC1D495E1C3527D1D8E" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="91193695FFC7FFC1D495E1C3527D1D8E" blockId="27.[151,1437,253,2037]" lastBlockId="28.[151,1436,151,392]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC7FFC6D495E1C3560D1BAB" bold="true" box="[199,335,1940,1965]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Comments.</emphasis>
The head of 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC7FFC6D5BAE1C1552F1BAB" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[488,621,1940,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardosoi">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC7FFC6D5BAE1C1552F1BAB" box="[488,621,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. cardosoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characteristic in being longer than wide and having maxillary stylets very close medially, touching each other in some specimens (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC7FFC6D73CE1EF54841BD7" box="[878,966,1976,2001]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–50" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[168,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[159,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 45–50. Holopothrips cardosoi sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (45) body; (46) head and pronotum; (47) metanotal sculpture; (48) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (49) spermatheca; (50) pelta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445198/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
), a trait that is shared with 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC7FFC6D147E1EE52D71BD6" authorityName="Costa Lima" authorityYear="1935" box="[1301,1429,1977,2000]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ananasi">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC7FFC6D147E1EE52D71BD6" box="[1301,1429,1977,2000]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. ananasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC7FFC6D558E18956CF1BF3" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[266,397,2012,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardosoi">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC7FFC6D558E18956CF1BF3" box="[266,397,2012,2037]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. cardosoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks the characteristic sculpture formed by small equiangular reticles that 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC7FFC6D08AE18952161BF2" authorityName="Costa Lima" authorityYear="1935" box="[1240,1364,2013,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ananasi">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC7FFC6D08AE18952161BF2" box="[1240,1364,2013,2037]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">H. ananasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has in the head and metanotum, and has the antennal segments shorter and more robust. Another remarkable trait of this species is the lack of anteroangular pore plates in males, bearing only the posterior transverse band on sternites VII–VIII (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC0FFC1D55FE68856261CFE" box="[269,356,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–50" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1970,1993]" captionTargetBox="[168,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[159,1409,455,1948]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 45–50. Holopothrips cardosoi sp. nov. holotype and paratypes. (45) body; (46) head and pronotum; (47) metanotal sculpture; (48) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (49) spermatheca; (50) pelta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445198/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC0FFC1D528E688553B1CFE" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[378,633,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardosoi">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D528E688553B1CFE" box="[378,633,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Holopothrips cardosoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be related to some other large, dark-bodied species of the genus with two pairs of epimeral setae, such as 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC0FFC1D60DE75255AD1D1B" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[607,751,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlanticus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D60DE75255AD1D1B" box="[607,751,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. atlanticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC0FFC1D776E75254ED1D1A" authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[804,943,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrisetis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D776E75254ED1D1A" box="[804,943,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. nigrisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8E157FCFFC0FFC1D7E7E75354B61D1B" box="[949,1012,260,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D7E7E75354B61D1B" bold="true" box="[949,1012,260,285]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(both with V-shaped maxillary stylets instead of parallel, and three pore plates on sternite VIII instead of one), and 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC0FFC1D056E77E533B1D46" authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[1028,1145,297,320]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrum" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D056E77E533B1D46" box="[1028,1145,297,320]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8E157FCFFC0FFC1D0D3E77053831D46" box="[1153,1217,295,320]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" rank="species">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D0D3E77053831D46" bold="true" box="[1153,1217,295,320]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(which has closely striate metanotal sculpture instead of reticles). This species induces terminal rosette galls on an undetermined 
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D4C5E72657A51D8E" box="[151,231,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Myrcia</emphasis>
species (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC0FFC1D51CE73856D31D8E" box="[334,401,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1630,1653]" captionTargetBox="[234,1352,184,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[234,1352,183,1606]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Leaf-galls induced by Holopothrips (white arrows). (1) galls on Siphoneugena reitzii (by H. curiosus); (2) galls on Myrciaria floribunda (by H. spermathecus) (Photo: André Santana); (3) gall on Myrcia guianensis (by H. molzi); (4) gall on Myrcia retorta (by H. striatus); (5) gall on Myrcia sp. (by H. cardosoi) (Photo: João C. Cardoso); (6) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. conducans); (7) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. longisetus); (8) gall on Myrcia selloi (by H. acrioris); (9) galls on Neomitranthes obscura (by H. varicolor) (Photo: Sheila Carvalho-Fernandes)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445184/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), very similar in structure to that induced by 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC0FFC1D7D9E72653671D8E" authorityName="Priesner" authorityYear="1921" box="[907,1061,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Thysanoptera (awaiting allocation)" genus="Phrasterothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conducans">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D7D9E72653671D8E" box="[907,1061,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">H. conducans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FFC0FFC1D01BE726539E1D8E" box="[1097,1244,367,392]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FFC0FFC1D01BE726539E1D8E" box="[1097,1244,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">M. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FFC0FFC1D0BEE73852721D8E" box="[1260,1328,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1630,1653]" captionTargetBox="[234,1352,184,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[234,1352,183,1606]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–9. Leaf-galls induced by Holopothrips (white arrows). (1) galls on Siphoneugena reitzii (by H. curiosus); (2) galls on Myrciaria floribunda (by H. spermathecus) (Photo: André Santana); (3) gall on Myrcia guianensis (by H. molzi); (4) gall on Myrcia retorta (by H. striatus); (5) gall on Myrcia sp. (by H. cardosoi) (Photo: João C. Cardoso); (6) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. conducans); (7) gall on Myrcia splendens (by H. longisetus); (8) gall on Myrcia selloi (by H. acrioris); (9) galls on Neomitranthes obscura (by H. varicolor) (Photo: Sheila Carvalho-Fernandes)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445184/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
